, personal freedom, and moral and economic value. Their ethnographically grounded accounts show how taxation may be influenced by spaces of fiscal sovereignty that exist outside or alongside the state, taking various forms, from alternative religious communities to economic collectives.  afunded by Berghahn Open Anthro, in partnership with Libraria  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEconomic anthropology. 0aSocial contractxEconomic aspects. 0aTaxationxSocial aspects. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Taxation / General.2bisacsh1 aBäumer Escobar, Vinzenz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEräsaari, Matti, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKauppinen, Anna-Riikka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMakovicky, Nicolette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMakovicky, Nicolette, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSheild Johansson, Miranda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Robin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVenkatesan, Soumhya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVicol, Dora-Olivia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb2 aBerghahn Open Anthro, in partnership with Librariaefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800739956?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800739956zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/978